@node "fe7" "Amiga"

@{fg shine} THE AMIGA's History and Future@{fg text}

   The Amiga has come a long way since the beginning and has changed
owners several times. Fortunately the Amiga survived and will hopefully
rise to Top position again.

   This document contains the history of the Amiga compiled from what I
have read the last couple of years since I bought my A1200. And remember
this is essential information for any Amiga user.

   As we all surely know the Amiga's life began in 1985. Amiga ( the
company ) developed a groundbreaking machine codenamed, Lorraine. But they
ran into financial trouble and Commodore Business Machines bought their
shares. Lorraine then got more memory and was released as the Commodore
Amiga A1000.
  It was the most amazing machine : 4096 colour, genlockable graphics,
digital sound ( at a time when PCs were mono beepers ) ,a powerful CPU
and a graphics orientated efficient multitasking OS. It sold for $1000+ 
and was selling well because of its wonderful capabilities.

   In 1987-89 the A500 and the A2000 were launched. The A2000 a PC
competitor (lots of slots) and the A500 an Atari competitor.
   The A500 succeeded to beat the Atari and the A2000 were mainly bought
by Graphics artists - it failed to make an impact in the hallowed business
market.

   1990-91 saw the launch of the overdue A3000. Workbench 2, 32-bit,
68030, SCSI, ECS and the ability to use standard SVGA monitors were some
of the exciting new feutures. It was sleek and fast and many Amiga users
rate it as the best Amiga ever made.
   The Video Toaster & Lightwave 3D were also released during this time
and the Amiga would never be the same again. Almost all NTSC TV producers 
adopted the Amiga and the result was professional 3D graphics in TV
productions for 10 times less money and effort than Workstations. ( Just 
check Seaquest DSV, Babylon 5 and Robocop the series ).
   The doomed CDTV ( an A500 in a Hi-Fi box with a CD-ROM ) was also   
launched. Commodore knew CD-ROM was the way forward but couldn't implement
it correctly. The CDTV also did more harm to the Amiga name than good.

  1992... This is were everything really started to go wrong. New management 
proved fatal to the Amiga.  The Original Management pushed 2 systems:

-The A3000+ was basically an AGA A3000 with the inclusion of the AT&T
DSP32. The DSP was very powerful and could emulate a V.42 bis FAX/Data 
Modem through SOFTWARE! It was of such that it would've cost the same as
the original A3000 - even with the AGA and DSP!

-The A1000+ was a super-low-cost 2slot AGA Amiga. The case was like the   
A1000 but without the keyboard space. CPU was going to be either a 28mhz
68020 or a 68EC030. It was going to cost $999 with 2mb or 4mb.

  What happened was that the projects were scrapped by the new management
and the A600 was built - it cost more than the A500 and did less! Then they
tried an ECS A1000+ design but it cost much more than the original AGA 
A1000+ design and was also binned.

Then they took the ECS A1000+ design ( an hacked up A3000 design in a bad
case ) and made the A3200. The A3200 was a very hacked AGA-based A3000 in 
a very bad case. The case was so bad they had to put the CPU on a seperate
card to make it fit. This CPU card wasn't even really reworked for this
design and only worked properly with an 68030. The cost was so high
Commodore plugged in a 68040 which didn't really work properly and
called the machine the A4000. ( Now you know why the A4000 has got slow
memory access ) Even the SCSI-interface was removed and they replaced it
with slow IDE. The engineering team was very frustrated but they tried to
make the best out of it by using 72pin SIMMs and including a better Buster 
for Zorro-III.
  
  1993: The A4000 was released in it's very hacked up form. Many cried
over the missing SCSI-interface and Flicker Fixer.
                                                                              
  The Flicker Fixer was an excellent idea and the exclusion of this also
harmed the Amiga name as most Amigas were now used with low-resolution
flickering 15khz TV Monitors - not even PCs used such a monitor.
  Okay, you could buy a MultiScan but they were ( and still are ) very
scarce and expensive.
  All was not bad though. AGA was better than PC VGA and Workbench 3 was
released. There was also support for VGAs with the DoublePAL mode but 
this only worked in OS-friendly programs and halved the AGA bandwidth.
  The A1200 appeared later. This machine took the A500 idea of cramming
in as much as possible. 68020, AGA, Workbench 3, even the IDE looked like
a good idea! Although the PCMCIA interface didn't prove that useful as it 
was supposed to be. Many Amiga Users see this as the Ultimate Amiga and 
not the A4000.
  Development started on the AAA chipset which promised better graphics
as well as an overdue sound upgrade.
  
  1994: The CD32 was released. Basically it was an CDTV Mark II but
based on the A1200 with the inclusion of the slow Akiko Chunky to Planar
converter. This was supposed to be a console to compete against Sega and 
the likes. Once again it did a lot of harm to the Amiga image. Why did 
Commodore bother? They could've added an CD-ROM to the A1200 or A4000 as 
standard which would've been a much bigger success. They knew they
should've concentrated on the PC and Macintosh market but no, they wanted
to create a useless games machine instead of tackling the serious computer 
market with much bigger benefits.
  Workbench 3.1 was also released with CD-ROM support and as an upgrade
to all Amigas.
  The A4000T got released just before the Commodore liquidation.   
Basically it was the high-end machine the A4000 never was. SCSI, more 
expansion slots, tower case, some DMA problems solved, unfortunately still
no Flicker Fixer.
  Behind the scenes Commodore planned a RISC Amiga. The Hewlett Packard   
PA RISC was their CPU choice as it had good 68000 compatibility. They also
planned a 3D RISC custom chip for the new Amiga, unfortunately the
inevitable happened.
  Commodore US filed for liquidation on 29 April 1994. The rest of the   
Amiga world seemed unaffected and 3rd-party development for the Amiga 
continued although some of the bigger companies pulled out.
  Two months later JAY MINER, one of the designers of the Amiga regardes
as the "Father of the Amiga" passed away on June 20, 1994. A huge loss to 
the Amiga Community.
  
  1995: Escom bought Commodore after a year and relaunched the Amiga on   
30 May 1995.

But beforehand they bought most of the bankrupt High Street stores in   
England - a huge capital investment - that later proved to much for them.
  They re-released the A1200 and A4000T as well as Multiscan monitors
for Amigas. But the Amiga had not been developed for over a year then and 
wasn't that competitive anymore. Although it was still superior to the 
PC ( which haven't even got a decent OS or architecture ( or users ;D ) 
in many ways.
  Apple Macintosh started using the PowerPC RISC processor putting it
way in front of the Amiga in terms of power.

   1996: The first new Amiga prototype got reveiled at CeBIT show.   
  Project Walker looked radically different and got billed the "vacuum   
cleaner". It had a 68EC030 CPU, Standard HDD and 4x CD, 2MB Chip & 4MB FAST
Memory, Better I/O Controller, Workbench 3.2 and a new expansion slot. 
Amiga Tecnologies claimed it will be available by Spring but eventually 
the project got scrapped.
  In July Escom filed for liquidation. The future definately didn't look
too bright. More Amiga developers lost their hope and Newtek ( who 
originally made the Video Toaster ) stopped developing Lightwave 3D for 
the Amiga as it made more profit in the PC market.
  To make matters even worse the PC got a hacked attempt at Multitasking   
in the form of Windows 95 - the competition for the new Amigas was going 
to be fierce.

   1997...(NOW) The future started looking bright again early in the   
year.

Two Amiga compatible PowerPC machines were announced.

-PIOS ONE ,the less compatible of the two, was already in prototype
stages as it was based around standard components. It ran BeOS, a new
multitasking alternative OS from Be Inc.and pOS, an OS from ProDAD.

-The A\Box from Phase 5 was and is still in the development stages but   
it promises a lot. The base of the system is the unique 128bit 
CAIPIRINHA chip.The system has Monitor output as well as Video & Audio 
Inputs and Outputs. The OS is an AmigaOS 3.1 Exec mixed with UNIX for
Multiprocessor, MultiUser etc. support as well as an "Amiga Virtual
Machine" which promises to run original 680x0 Amiga binaries. A truly
amazing machine (just like the original A1000 was ) and they expect it 
to sell for Pentium prices ( with the Video & Audio Inputs included! ).
   The BIG NEWS of 1997 was the acquisition of Amiga Technologies by
GATEWAY 2000, a company with revenue earnings for 1996 exceeding $5 
billion. At last the Amiga has money and power behind it.
   Until now they haven't revealed their plan yet but they are selling
Amiga licenses.
   Licensees so far include:  

- Micronik who released A1200-based systems in a tower with Zorro
slots.  
- Index who designed new AGA-based systems with 30% faster Chip RAM and
in a standard form factor. They will be mainly used in Point-Of-Sale
Systems & Multimedia kiosks.
- DCE who designed two new motherboards: 030,AGA  ( A5000 )
					 060,AGA  ( A6000 )
  Both these has an integrated scan doubler and outputs to standard VGA
monitors!!!
  They also have a video slot and optional MPEG decoder.
- Cloanto who will develop an PC Amiga Emulator - "Amiga Forever".
  Rest assured though - these emulators barely touches A500 speed on an
P200 MMX ( which has 5 times the CPU power of an 060! ).
- As well as numerous other less important licensees.

   What has the FUTURE got in store for us ?
Although the Amiga has survived its ordeal, it had not been developed
for the past couple of years because of the financial diffuculties its
parent companies had suffered. It is not that far behind though. The 
Amiga still has an superior OS and every now and then its custom chips 
delivers a surprise. But we do need a new processor and a more modern
custom chipset to regain market share. That won't be too hard as the PC 
hasn't even got a decent architecture or OS ( or users ;-) ) and the 
Macintosh is heading the same way with their CHRP systems. ( Apparently 
the first revisions can't use IDE devices )
   Therefore the FUTURE of the Amiga is bright. GATEWAY 2000 will 
successfully re-introduce the Amiga as they know a lot about marketing 
( the one thing Commodore lacked ).
   The Amiga will also definately upgrade to the PowerPC RISC as future   
CPU.   
   And we probably wouldn't have to wait that long for new Amigas as the
A\Box might as well become the next Amiga with licensing from GATEWAY 2000.
   I think Amiga International will be looking more into developing the
AmigaOS. Some features the next AmigaOS might include will JAVA, a TCP/IP 
stack and much better devices support as well as advanced RTG Graphics 
and Audio.
   Meanwhile Petro Tyschtschenko announced a Computer - Console - TV -   
Setup Box - Internet acesss - System for Xmas '98 at the Computer '97 
show ( Rumour has it that it will use the ill-fated Walker's case and
will also include a Vacuum cleaner ;-) ) and that AmigaOS 3.5 will 
*hopefully* be released in Spring 1998.
   But the question remains - shouldn't a PowerPC based Amiga be
released then ?  
   This is the only option to remain competive.  
   Are they heading the wrong way again ?  
   Are they over-estimating the Amiga - user's patience ?

   Only time will tell. Remember though that we already survived two 
bankruptcies - so things can only get better. And the Amiga OS is still 
the most powerful, efficient Operating System on any platform.


			---------------------------------
			-	Amiga is alive !	-
			---------------------------------  

Cheers.  

Bertus Viljoen  

This document was written on 9 October 1997 on an Amiga A1200.
Updated on 17 December 1997 for Amiga Information Online.
Please excuse any grammar or concord errors as English is my Second   
Language.

