@node "fe14" "Face Up to the fact"

@{fg shine} The future of the Amiga@{fg text}

Where ever one looks, it`s in our faces...

"Amiga is alive",
"Amiga is coming back",
"Escom will save us",
"Amiga international will save us",
"Gateway 2000 will save us",
"The Abox will rule!".

The truth is NO commercial company will save the Amiga! I cannot believe
some people`s optimism, the Amiga is dead as a commecial platform. What we
have left is no more than dedicated hobbyists and even they cannot revive
the old Amiga spirit. Everything is just a farce, lazyness took us all.
Instead of using the Amiga`s greatest assets, coders resort to PC style
coding which on an 020, 030, 040 or even an 060 processor leaves the Amiga
lightyears behind. 

But what about the Power PC chip? That`s all very well, but who`s going to
develop for it? Can you really expect billionaire companies who are selling
close on a million copies of their software on the PC to give a new machine
a second thought? The world is run by fat cats who care only about money so
a bit of dedication is just a joke. It all comes down to unrealistic
idealism, striving to make the most powerful machine without consideration
of sales. The idea is staring these developers in the face, instead of
making a Power PC chip for the Amiga it would be so obvious to make an Intel
chip addon. The prices of Intel chips are much better value and besides that
it would give Amiga owners the best of the PC world too, with full PC
compatability. The ideal way to go is not the processor; its the custom
hardware. Look how fast a processor the PC needs to scroll at 25fps, look
at their lousy sprite handling, yet the amiga was developed to do these
tasks. Nowdays the PC and the Playstation have adopted the same theory,
instead of relying on their processors they have specifically created 3d fx
chips in order to increase performance of 3d routines. This is the
direction the Amiga needs to take.

What is the fuss about system friendly software these days? The Amiga is a
far more capable machine than even the original creators suspected, but by
limiting coding to system friendly tasks they are limiting themselves to
the original standards set for them. System software looks ugly, unoriginal
and in most cases is so damn buggy. The PC is becoming a far greater
inspiration than we need. If it wasn`t for the Amiga logo and the amiga 
keys I would think I was using a low spec PC.

So what does the Amiga have in its favour? Well to be accutely to the
point; absoloutely nothing! Everything seen on the Amiga these days is
either low spec PC style s**t or ammateur PD quality stuff. It`s impossible
to log onto a BBS these days and not find stupid little programs like
a workbench tamigotchi or pre releases of workbench replacements.. in most
cases affecting the compatability of software anyway. MUI for example, the
buggy Workbench degrader takes up loads of Hard drive space, eats memory
and does f**k all?! Then, dumbass developers decide that their programs
will only run under MUI.

As for software publishers, well there`s Vulcan.. a team made famous for
their audacity to release a commercial Amos game and then there`s some
shareware publishers. Who really wants to release years of hard work into 
the hands of these people?

The Amiga has no future the way things are going, users are too interested
in trying to keep the pace of the PC and high spec consoles that we have
lost our heritage. Dammit, if we wanted to see this kinda s**t we wouldn`t
have an Amiga surely? Don`t get me wrong I love the Amiga, but only for
its past releases,  I find far more enjoyment watching old demos and playing
old games than I could find in whatever Gateway 2000 or whoever comes next
could possibly offer. Accept the truth, the AMIGA has no future!

By Wade/Gods^Seenpoint Staff

@{b}NOTE:@{ub} The comments made above are of the writters own choice and in
no way do they represent AIO it's editor and it's staffs opinions. AIO
does not agree with what has been said above, but if you have any comments
to make about this text email : Cool@Dcandy.demon.co.uk.@{ub}

