@endnode

@node "fe15" "UAE"

@{fg shine} UAE@{fg text}

 I am in an awkward position. I have used an Amiga over the last 7 years
or so for most of my things. Well in the last year or so my Amiga (a
1200) has started to cough and splutter until a few weeks ago it went
positively pear shaped. I'll switch it on, the hard drive makes a rather
feeble sound that I would guess is it trying to spin upto speed, the
little yellow light goes on and off many times, lots of peculiar noises
are emitted and then, after ten minutes of so the grinding noises start.
Soon after that I get a nice screen that says error of block "big
number" so I click cancel. But as soon as I've clicked on the thing
another one comes up and so on. I found myself yearning for the
simplicity of the PC, where in the past I have marveled at its ability  
to lose 17 megs of data and give me the option to recover it in 16k  
chunks which have interesting names like file0128.chk, most of which are  
just garbage anyway.

 Well I'm afraid I can no longer justify any further repair or expansion
to my Amiga. There is simply not enough good software to justify it. My
486 runs Windows 95, Word 7, Excel and Encarta and that is all I really
need. Wordworth is too clunky and unreliable for me at least and the
encyclopedia software I have seen simply did not compare will Encarta
and Comptons for the PC. 20

 Now I think it's a shame that I am having to give up the Amiga because
I learnt computers from it. I know the platform inside and out, (before
this year anyway) and I have lots of little bits of software that
occasionally I would like to use that I just can't get on the PC. For  
instance, Dpaint IV. I have used that for all my limited art needs since
I had the machine, it is very handy and flexible. I have found nothing  
on my PC that matches it for ease of use and the amount of control you
can actually exercise over the pointer. The PC port is not very good,
it's old and clunky. I would like to use Dpaint for graphics on my
web-site when it's finally up and running. But my Amiga has gone senile,
so what can I do?

 The question plagued me for minutes until when I stumbled across the
site for Uae. This is a Amiga emulation based on a core of C code, which
gives a great amount of portability with a trade-off for speed. There
are versions for linux, Mac, Acorn, X-Windows and PC in DOS and Windows  
95/Direct-X flavours. I shall concentrate on the Windows 95/DirectX
version. It provides a almost complete emulation of an 020 based ECS
Amiga complete with FPU. Not only that it emulates a Picasso96
compatible graphics card  to give an overall speed increase in graphics
and processor emulation, cutting out custom chip emulation. AHI is
emulated so you can have direct access to your 16 bit sound-card. You
need about 16 megs of free memory to run it well.

 Installing and configuring is fairly simple although you do need a
fairly good knowledge of the working of the Amiga Workbench so you can
set up the hard disk. I set up version 0.6.9 release 13 although by the
time you read this version 0.7 should have been released. You get to
select your configuration at startup. You can define how much memory
goes to the Amiga (24 megs is the maximum, I think), how you emulate the
sound, graphics, the joystick and serial etc.. There is one key problem
with emulating an Amiga on a PC. That is that PC drives cannot read and
write Amiga Format disks, whether or not they are high density or double
density.  Floppies have to been converted to an ADF file via a real
Amiga using Transdisk a widely available utility that appears in some
releases of the WinUAE archive. There is a hardware solution that can be
found on the internet but this only allows you to read a whole floppy in
one go, creating an ADF file. You can select the floppies images you
want to boot up from, "inserting" them into the virtual drive. WinUAE  
appears to read the floppies straight off the hard disk rather than  
copying them into memory. On Rob Stewart's Packard Bell 233mhz MMX  
Pentium a floppy image works about the same speed as a floppy. 20

To get going you need an image of the Kickstart ROM. These can be  
obtained with ease from the internet or straight from your real Amiga  
using a tool such as Transrom. The ability to choose your ROM version
allows for a great range of compatibility. Games that I have not played  
for ages because they never ran on my A1200 such as North and South and
Pacmania suddenly become playable again.

 But the thing that knocks the spots of it for me is the hard disk
emulation. You have two options, use a hard file, slow clunky and
limited to the size you specify for it, or make the disk a standard
directory on the PC. This stunning feature makes disk access lightning
fast, as fast as your setup allows. Your only space constraints are
those of the PC drive, you can access all the Amiga files from the PC.
You can even use tools such as drivespace to compress your Amiga drive,
completely transparently to the Amiga. I've heard that there are one or
two problems with foreign characters in filenames not supported by the  
VFAT 32 file system, but I've never come across them. Or at least I
think I haven't. I have a strange problem that whenever I try to install
MUI 3.8, Win 95 gets called up and then everything locks up. So maybe it
is a problem.  20

 O.k. all this is fine, but how does the emulation run? Well I haven't
tested it extensively but I have not come across any huge problems in
the emulation. On my Intel 486 50mhz it runs at about 1/4 the speed of
an Amiga 500. On Rob Stewart's machine it runs (according to Aibb 6.5)
at about 2.33 mips which is faster than an out of the box A1200,
although I would have said it's a bit faster than that. This does not
however mean that you get a perfect nippy A500. Sound emulation can get
very choppy on Rob Stewart's machine when set to 44khz stereo, but works
fine when set to 22khz mono, which should be fine for most games anyway.
All Terrain Racing ran very well and that's got all sorts going on in
it. I've been told on the internet that it runs like a A500 on a P100  
and I had it running fast on a P90. 20

The Picasso96 emulation means you can have screens limited only by your
available memory and your graphics card. You can access any PC device by
setting up a hard disk, though as yet I have found no way of setting up
the CD-ROM as a CD-ROM drive so you get the right labels etc.

 One of the big things this opens up is the world of notebooks. You can
get notebooks with practically every Pentium processor available at the
moment. It is a much more attractive option than that hideous A600
notebook kit. You can have loads of memory, a nippy A600 equivalent (on
a fast Pentium) a 24bit display, 16 bit sound and CD-ROM etc. only
dependent on the hardware limitations of the machine you are using.

 Anyway, if you have a fairly nippy PC, UAE offers you a very usable
Amiga that can take advantage of memory, graphics cards, sound cards,

CD-ROM drives and a range of other hardware that would otherwise be very
expensive to fit. I would like to see it be able to take advantage of a
midi interface on the sound card or any bit in synth capabilities such
as the OPL3 chipset which is on most PC sound cards, aswell as wavetable
sounds. Also it would be nice if it could read Amiga disks straight off
the PC drive. I know there are bits of software that can get some types
of floppy drive to read and write a special PC 1.72 meg format as
opposed to the standard 1.44 high density limit. As 1.72 megs can be
stored on an Amiga disk I would guess that it means that the formats  
must use a similar type of encoding. Some top quality Ex-Amiga, now PC,
hacker needs to have a real go at it. However, such an emulation really
is a feat which I would have thought nearly impossible, especially in C.  
The code is very quick, despite what anyone says, although Fellow, it's
only opposition, which I have had limited experience of, is supposed to  
run like the clappers because it is pure assembly code. But it only runs
from on a PC in DOS, lacks the range of good compatibility and Picasso96
emulation and the interface isn't very pretty. 20

So maybe it isn't time to bin your A1200 yet but I think WinUAE is
great. O.k. so you can't play the AGA games on it but it's supposed to
run Gloom in Picasso96 mode and it's free so get it and get all your PC
owning friends to try it now!

I am the process of setting up a site that has all you need to get UAE
going. However in the meantime there is a great site that is definitely
worth visiting whether you are interested in emulating an Amiga or not.  
It is called Lazarus and it is at :-

http://www.erols.com/ccsystems/lazarus/ (I think).

If you have problems with that try www.uae.de for the official UAE
homepage where you can get versions of the software for many platforms.

Don't forget to visit my homepage at :-

http://freespace.virgin.net/david.wheeler1 and mail me on

thefaceis@unforgettable.com

