@{b}From@{ub} : Galahad of Fairlight

  For what its worth, here is my opinion on Gateway 2000 and Amiga
International.

  Gateway 2000 are a big company, certainly big enough to re-launch the
Amiga in whatever guise.  That is the problem.  No-one really knows what
guise the Amiga is going to take.  Just about every week, another
annoucement goes by telling the world that another licensee of the Amiga
has been signed, and whilst this is good for the OCS/ECS/AGA market of
having more clone manufacturers, the news about the future direction of the
Amiga is somewhat shrouded with mystery and secrecy.  Why both Amiga
International and Gateway 2000 feel the need for 'cloak and dagger' tactics
is beyond me!

  The Amiga has always thrived from the 'bedroom' coder.  Just about anyone
could afford an Amiga, and with a little perseverance, anyone could get the
Amiga to do something.  As the old slogan from Commodore said, 'the only
limit is your imagination.'  Well I think that have gotten out of the 680x0
series of Amiga's as much as they can.  They've driven back the boundaries
by producing games that were supposed to have been impossible on the Amiga
(Doom clones).  I used to be constantly surprised by the abilities of
coders on the Amiga, but that hasn't happened for a long while.

  Many Amiga coders have the ideas and the drive to make things bigger and
more spectacular than that of their PC coding cousins, but can't realise
their full potential because of the lack of an upgrade path with the 680x0
series.  The 68060 is the highest we can get, and that is way short of the
processing power of a modern PC, a PowerPC equipped Macintosh, Playstation
and the SH2 equipped Saturn.

  I don't think many people care anymore WHAT processor the new generation
of Amiga will have, but they might like to know in advance so that they can
get to grips with the processor now.  Quality software drives a Quality
computer, if and when the new Amiga gets released, I think it might be in
better shape with plenty of software available on its release.  Or are the
major software companies going to get the first start on these machines,
and the rest of us that supported the Amiga through thick and thin will be
subjected as 'those that can wait'?

  I think the Amiga is good machine, Gateway 2000, Amiga International and
those that support the Amiga, can make it a GREAT machine again.  We all
want to help make the Amiga #1 again, how about a little help from Gateway
2000 and Amiga International to make that possible?

Signed Galahad of Fairlight

@{b}From@{ub} : Robert Wheeler

 I think that is now time to face facts. The only way that the Amiga
will have any chance of surviving as a platform depend on people being
ready to buy software for it. No one wants to buy the machine at the  
moment, lets face it, all you get for  A3700 is an Amiga with a 030 that
may be able to run an O.k. but rather clunky WordWorth. You can get a  
166mhz Pentium complete with Windows 95 and Office 97 for around that
price if you look in the right places. The only way the Amiga can
progress is if Gateway 2000 sit down and serious rework the custom
chips. At the moment all I have seen of "new Amigas" is processor and  
graphics upgrades that move away from the custom chips, the very things
that make an Amiga an Amiga. The core of the Amiga operating system is
still better than any other, if a little buggy. It still has the
potential to wipe out the PC. The ever decreasing readership of Amiga  
Format and CU Amiga seems to indicate that less and less people are  
using Amigas and supposedly they are moving to PC. We need to form a
familiarity with the Amiga system with the users of other systems, which
will inevitably create a demand for software to run on it and perhaps a
demand for new machines. Meanwhile the boffins at Gateway 2000 should be
able to come up with something worthwhile. But we need improvements on
existing software and a real killer application such as a word
processor. It wouldn't be hard to make a few improvements to Wordsworth.  
If we show people what could be done on an Amiga, and make it clear that
the emulation is only a emulation is only the equivalent of a budget  
Amiga then maybe we could lure some of the more dumb people who would
usually buy a PC into going for a cheaper Amiga setup. This would create
a demand for software and then some good stuff would start being  
produced, attracting the less dumb people. In the end Amigas could
emerge with a worthy reputation. Possibly............

